02:51.880 --> 02:53.000
There you go.

02:54.320 --> 02:57.600
Signed, sealed and delivered.

02:57.640 --> 02:59.040
Thanks, Pete.

03:01.440 --> 03:04.320
Pete, what was the name of that bar we were in

03:01.440 --> 03:04.320
on Sunday night?

03:05.080 --> 03:06.160
The Bullet Bar.

03:06.200 --> 03:07.440
That's the one.

03:12.400 --> 03:13.760
DISCO: Oi, oi, oi! JIM: Oh, come on!

03:13.800 --> 03:15.160
DISCO: What's going on?

03:15.200 --> 03:16.600
VINCE: I'll check the fuse box.

03:16.640 --> 03:18.200
PETE: Well, it's not going to be the fuse box, is it?

03:18.240 --> 03:19.880
It'll be another bloody power cut.

03:19.920 --> 03:21.840
JIM: Right, I'm going for the fagarettes.

03:21.880 --> 03:23.560
PETE: Bloody Caribbean.

03:27.880 --> 03:30.200
Can't wait to get back home.

03:30.240 --> 03:32.360
What, to the wind and the rain? Nutter!

03:32.400 --> 03:35.720
Yeah, yeah, yeah, working electricity

03:32.400 --> 03:35.720
and sanity.

03:35.760 --> 03:36.920
What?

03:41.480 --> 03:42.560
Stevie!

03:43.600 --> 03:44.840
No!

03:44.880 --> 03:46.520
The electricity's live!

04:24.040 --> 04:25.440
Good afternoon, sir.

04:25.480 --> 04:27.520
Er, sorry, nobody's in the station,

04:27.560 --> 04:29.520
so I thought I'd make myself useful out here.

04:29.560 --> 04:30.720
Watering the flowers.

04:30.760 --> 04:31.760
They looked a bit dry.

04:32.760 --> 04:33.880
JP.

04:33.920 --> 04:35.360
JP, yes, of course, of course.

04:35.400 --> 04:36.800
It's today, is it?

04:36.840 --> 04:38.600
Yeah, well, of course it's today.

04:36.840 --> 04:38.600
Yeah, um, sorry.

04:38.640 --> 04:42.440
Er, we were up late, er, solving a case last night,

04:38.640 --> 04:42.440
and, uh... And...

04:45.480 --> 04:47.040
Oh, I'm so sorry, sir.

04:47.080 --> 04:48.440
-Little bit wet. -Yes.

04:48.480 --> 04:50.480
-I'm so sorry about that, sir. -Don't worry.

04:50.520 --> 04:52.800
Don't worry about it, JP. It's just a wet shoe.

04:52.840 --> 04:54.600
No, I'll find... Yes, no, no, no.

04:52.840 --> 04:54.600
I've got that, sir.

04:54.640 --> 04:56.440
I just need to get my shoe off.

04:56.480 --> 04:57.880
And I will be fine.

04:57.920 --> 05:00.440
Get it dry, I can do that. I can do it, thank you.

05:00.480 --> 05:02.280
-Give me your socks. -No, I will deal

05:00.480 --> 05:02.280
with my socks.

05:02.320 --> 05:04.880
-Honestly, no, you're tickling my foot!

05:02.320 --> 05:04.880
-The water, it's everywhere.

05:04.920 --> 05:06.320
Good afternoon, sir.

05:12.400 --> 05:14.760
-You must be JP. -Oh, yes, of course.

05:12.400 --> 05:14.760
You two have not met. Er, allow me to introduce you

05:14.800 --> 05:17.160
to, er, PC Hooper.

05:20.960 --> 05:24.760
Um, this is the bit where people

05:20.960 --> 05:24.760
usually say hello.

05:24.800 --> 05:27.800
-Oh, yes, er, hello. -Hello.

05:27.840 --> 05:29.880
Er, PC Hooper, this is, er, Sergeant...

05:29.920 --> 05:32.120
Sorry, Detective Sergeant Cassell.

05:32.160 --> 05:34.160
Yes, well, it's a new day for all of us, isn't it?

05:34.200 --> 05:35.920
You a PC, you a DS.

05:37.240 --> 05:39.760
Yes, well, I've got a new pen... Somewhere.

05:43.440 --> 05:44.640
CASSELL: Honore Police Station?

05:44.680 --> 05:46.240
I should have answered the phone, shouldn't I?

05:46.280 --> 05:48.200
Oh, don't worry about it, JP.

05:48.240 --> 05:50.680
I'm sure we'll find plenty of things for you to do,

05:48.240 --> 05:50.680
other than watering flowers.

05:52.080 --> 05:53.560
That was Dwayne.

05:53.600 --> 05:56.160
We have a death at the Scorpion Lounge

05:53.600 --> 05:56.160
recording studio.

05:56.200 --> 05:58.000
Gosh. Right, well, we'd better get down there.

05:58.040 --> 05:59.880
Er, after you, JP. We'll see you down there.

05:59.920 --> 06:01.520
I'm really sorry, sir.

06:03.720 --> 06:04.720
Er, Florence?

06:05.480 --> 06:06.880
Yes?

06:06.920 --> 06:10.800
Er, I think it'll take us a while to find our rhythm.

06:10.840 --> 06:12.440
As it were, erm,

06:12.480 --> 06:14.680
but, er, what I'd like to say is that

06:14.720 --> 06:16.440
if you'll agree to be patient with me,

06:16.480 --> 06:19.960
er, then I will agree to try and not be too much...

06:20.000 --> 06:21.840
Er, well, yeah, well, like myself, really.

06:21.880 --> 06:23.200
You know what I think?

06:23.240 --> 06:25.440
I think we should not worry about it.

06:25.480 --> 06:28.240
Just focus on the case and see how we go.

06:28.280 --> 06:30.280
I say, that sounds like a splendid idea.

06:30.320 --> 06:31.360
Uh, shall we?

06:33.560 --> 06:35.120
Yeah.

06:36.840 --> 06:39.920
I can't believe I'll be working with

06:36.840 --> 06:39.920
the legendary Dwayne Myers.

06:39.960 --> 06:42.480
I've heard so much about you at police college.

06:44.000 --> 06:45.680
Why wouldn't it be?

06:46.840 --> 06:47.960
Never mind.

06:48.000 --> 06:49.040
Chief?

06:50.000 --> 06:51.920
So, what have we got so far?

06:51.960 --> 06:54.280
A band from the UK, here to record an album.

06:54.320 --> 06:56.840
-Um...

06:56.880 --> 06:59.960
If you have to look it up, it's clearly no-one

06:56.880 --> 06:59.960
we'll have heard of.

07:00.000 --> 07:01.880
Yes, well, I may have.

07:01.920 --> 07:04.200
You don't seem the type to have your finger on

07:01.920 --> 07:04.200
the pulse of popular music.

07:04.240 --> 07:06.320
Especially Flowers Of Progress.

07:06.360 --> 07:08.560
-Never heard of them. -Me neither.

07:08.600 --> 07:10.440
-Er, no, sir.

07:11.080 --> 07:12.560
Flowers Of Progress?

07:13.920 --> 07:16.680
Flowers Of Progress are here on Saint

07:23.600 --> 07:24.800
Stevie Smith,

07:24.840 --> 07:27.560
habitual wild child and lead singer.

07:27.600 --> 07:29.280
Lived life on the edge.

07:29.320 --> 07:31.360
And died the ultimate rock 'n' roll death,

07:31.400 --> 07:33.520
electrocuted in the swimming pool.

07:34.400 --> 07:35.480
Okay, <i> merci.</i>

07:41.200 --> 07:43.840
So, whereabouts in the pool was the body discovered,

07:41.200 --> 07:43.840
Dwayne?

07:43.880 --> 07:47.320
Well, he was found floating just there, Chief.

07:47.360 --> 07:48.840
FLORENCE: If he was this end of the pool,

07:48.880 --> 07:50.640
he can't have knocked the lights in, himself.

07:50.680 --> 07:52.800
But why were the lights left on in the daylight?

07:52.840 --> 07:55.680
They weren't, but the power supply

07:52.840 --> 07:55.680
to them was.

07:56.640 --> 07:58.480
This was all set for tonight.

07:58.520 --> 08:03.200
An end-of-recording party, to thank local musicians,

07:58.520 --> 08:03.200
hotel employees,

08:03.240 --> 08:04.480
people like that, you know?

08:04.520 --> 08:06.480
All organised by the band's manager.

08:06.520 --> 08:09.760
So, the question is, how did the stage lights

08:06.520 --> 08:09.760
end up in the swimming pool?

08:09.800 --> 08:11.200
I think I can help you with that one, Chief.

08:11.240 --> 08:13.560
You see...

08:13.600 --> 08:16.760
-Pin needs to be in, to keep the leg in position.

08:13.600 --> 08:16.760
-Mmm-hmm.

08:16.800 --> 08:19.120
But look here, it's worn and weathered.

08:19.160 --> 08:21.960
I think the pin snapped and the whole thing fell

08:19.160 --> 08:21.960
into the swimming pool.

08:22.000 --> 08:24.160
-Here it is.

08:24.200 --> 08:25.480
No, don't touch it.

08:25.520 --> 08:28.400
Right.  I need a...

08:28.440 --> 08:30.080
Ah, yeah. Thank you, Florence.

08:32.480 --> 08:34.000
If you ask me, Chief,

08:34.040 --> 08:36.640
the poor guy just took his swim

08:34.040 --> 08:36.640
at precisely the wrong time.

08:36.680 --> 08:39.040
Yes, it does seem incredibly unfortunate,

08:36.680 --> 08:39.040
doesn't it?

08:39.080 --> 08:41.000
You don't think it was an accident?

08:41.040 --> 08:43.640
This pin didn't break, not of its own accord.

08:43.680 --> 08:44.960
It's been deliberately cut.

08:45.000 --> 08:46.320
Really?

08:46.360 --> 08:49.240
With some sort of hacksaw, as far as I can tell.

08:49.280 --> 08:51.880
Yes, look, the blade slipped, marking it there.

08:51.920 --> 08:54.440
And the end has burrs, it's not been

08:51.920 --> 08:54.440
sheared off clean. If this was a pin that

08:54.480 --> 08:57.000
just snapped after years of wear and tear,

08:57.040 --> 08:58.760
the break would be smooth, but this isn't.

08:58.800 --> 09:00.720
It was deliberately sawn in two.

09:00.760 --> 09:04.040
So, what, you think someone pushed

09:00.760 --> 09:04.040
the tripod into the pool,

09:04.080 --> 09:05.600
intending to kill Stevie?

09:05.640 --> 09:07.720
And then cut the pin to make it look like

09:05.640 --> 09:07.720
an accident. Yes.

09:07.760 --> 09:08.920
So it was a murder?

09:08.960 --> 09:10.320
I'd say so, JP. I need a bag. Er...

09:11.760 --> 09:13.320
Ah, thank you.

09:16.960 --> 09:18.080
Ah.

09:18.920 --> 09:20.400
That's funny. <i>Elateridae</i> family,

09:26.240 --> 09:28.320
more commonly known as the click beetle.

09:28.360 --> 09:29.960
A click beetle?

09:30.000 --> 09:32.400
Yes, so named because if they happen to find

09:30.000 --> 09:32.400
themselves upside down,

09:32.440 --> 09:34.680
then they can click their backs to throw

09:32.440 --> 09:34.680
themselves in the air

09:34.720 --> 09:36.920
and land the right way round. Amazing little things.

09:38.000 --> 09:39.720
-Yes.

09:41.400 --> 09:43.960
Yes, well, the thing is, this specific breed

09:41.400 --> 09:43.960
of click beetle,

09:44.000 --> 09:46.960
<i>Achrestus fortunei,</i> has never lived

09:44.000 --> 09:46.960
on Saint-Marie.

09:47.000 --> 09:49.560
They're endemic only to Martinique.

09:49.600 --> 09:51.440
So, how did it get here?

09:51.480 --> 09:53.280
Quite. How indeed?

09:56.760 --> 09:59.720
Dust for prints, photograph and bag anything of interest.

09:59.760 --> 10:01.480
-Sarge. -Thanks.

10:01.520 --> 10:03.720
-He is amazing.

10:03.760 --> 10:06.720
I mean, that was just amazing.

10:06.760 --> 10:08.800
He's got a lot better tricks up his sleeve.

10:08.840 --> 10:10.800
Just wait and see.

10:10.840 --> 10:12.160
This was your first album?

10:12.200 --> 10:13.640
PETE: It was our only album.

10:13.680 --> 10:16.960
-Yes, um...

10:18.200 --> 10:21.360
Stevie's death may not have been an accident.

10:21.400 --> 10:23.400
You what

10:23.440 --> 10:25.520
Razor-sharp as ever there, Jimbo.

10:25.560 --> 10:28.000
We're not ruling anything out at the moment.

10:28.040 --> 10:29.800
Who discovered Stevie's body?

10:29.840 --> 10:32.200
Ah, we did.

10:32.240 --> 10:34.240
-Pete Thunders. -Yes. Hey.

10:34.920 --> 10:36.680
And?

10:36.720 --> 10:40.880
And this is Jim Smith, bass player and

10:36.720 --> 10:40.880
was Stevie's brother.

10:40.920 --> 10:43.280
I'm sorry for your loss, Jim.

10:43.320 --> 10:44.960
What's your role in the band?

10:46.720 --> 10:48.480
I'm... I'm the guitarist.

10:49.560 --> 10:51.720
And vocalist, and, er, songwriter.

10:51.760 --> 10:53.680
Co-writer.

10:53.720 --> 10:55.920
Yeah, co-songwriter.

10:55.960 --> 10:58.360
-Er, Disco Biscuit,

10:55.960 --> 10:58.360
the drummer.

10:58.400 --> 11:00.640
Or, as most people know me these days,

11:00.680 --> 11:01.680
Duncan Roberts.

11:04.160 --> 11:05.200
And you are?

11:05.800 --> 11:07.720
Hello?

11:07.760 --> 11:10.640
Erm... Oh, Cheryl. Er, Cheryl Moore.

11:10.680 --> 11:11.880
I'm the band's manager.

11:11.920 --> 11:13.600
Oh, yes, you organised the party?

11:13.640 --> 11:14.760
That's right. That was all me.

11:15.560 --> 11:16.760
Okay, not all me.

11:16.800 --> 11:19.200
Um, the beer company was footing the bill.

11:19.240 --> 11:20.840
But, er, yes.

11:20.880 --> 11:23.400
-Vince, the producer.

11:23.440 --> 11:25.000
This is my place.

11:25.040 --> 11:27.480
Yeah. What time did you find Stevie?

11:27.520 --> 11:29.000
VINCE: After 12:00.

11:29.040 --> 11:31.640
That's when the power tripped out.

11:31.680 --> 11:32.920
Thank you.

11:32.960 --> 11:35.200
And when did you last see Stevie alive?

11:35.240 --> 11:37.600
When he left the studio to go for a swim.

11:37.640 --> 11:38.720
HUMPHREY: Regular thing, was it?

11:38.760 --> 11:40.920
He liked to be in the pool at 12:00.

11:40.960 --> 11:43.320
Mad dogs and Englishmen and all that, you know.

11:43.360 --> 11:46.400
Yes. And what time did he leave the studio?

11:46.440 --> 11:48.840
Some time round 11:00, 11:30?

11:48.880 --> 11:50.760
Yeah, around that time, yeah.

11:50.800 --> 11:53.880
I can find the exact time for you on the control desk,

11:50.800 --> 11:53.880
if you'd like.

11:53.920 --> 11:57.680
Er, and did any of you see Stevie alive

11:53.920 --> 11:57.680
after he left the studio?

11:57.720 --> 11:58.800
JIM: Hmm.

12:00.160 --> 12:03.760
Why did you decide to record here in Saint

12:03.800 --> 12:07.680
Um, yes, in, er... In 1991, The Flowers Of Progress

12:07.720 --> 12:09.000
recorded their first album in this very...

12:09.040 --> 12:10.440
Our only album.

12:10.480 --> 12:12.200
Yeah, in this very studio.

12:12.240 --> 12:13.600
So, we've returned to recapture

12:13.640 --> 12:16.000
the anarchic energy that fuelled that debut...

12:16.040 --> 12:19.240
No-one in Britain would have Stevie record in their studio.

12:19.280 --> 12:20.760
The band had... We'd just got back together...

12:20.800 --> 12:24.000
Yes, thanks to Grand Central Beer.

12:24.040 --> 12:27.440
There's a song on the first album called...

12:27.480 --> 12:29.600
<i>-Grand Central.</i> Track two. -Yes.

12:29.640 --> 12:31.920
Um, and a... A beer company in America

12:31.960 --> 12:33.800
with the same name heard the song

12:33.840 --> 12:35.520
and wanted to use it for a commercial.

12:35.560 --> 12:37.240
If the advert goes the way that we hope it will,

12:37.280 --> 12:40.160
then it could be a really great

12:37.280 --> 12:40.160
opportunity for the...

12:40.200 --> 12:41.320
This band.

12:46.200 --> 12:49.000
Where were you all at the time of Stevie's death,

12:46.200 --> 12:49.000
when the power tripped out?

12:49.040 --> 12:50.960
We were all in the studio.

12:51.000 --> 12:54.800
At 12:00, when the lights fell in the pool and

12:51.000 --> 12:54.800
Stevie was electrocuted,

12:54.840 --> 12:57.920
you were all there, all of you, inside the studio?

12:58.480 --> 12:59.680
Mmm-hmm. Yeah.

12:59.720 --> 13:01.480
-Mmm-hmm. -Yeah.

13:05.400 --> 13:07.080
HUMPHREY: Okay.

13:07.120 --> 13:10.360
So, all five people in there claim they were together

13:07.120 --> 13:10.360
in the studio

13:10.400 --> 13:13.560
when the lighting rig entered the pool

13:10.400 --> 13:13.560
and electrocuted Stevie.

13:13.600 --> 13:15.640
There's a security fence around the whole place.

13:15.680 --> 13:18.240
The only way to get out here is to come through the villa.

13:18.280 --> 13:20.120
Then someone who was allowed in.

13:20.160 --> 13:21.720
The band didn't set up all this.

13:21.760 --> 13:23.360
DWAYNE: I already checked.

13:23.400 --> 13:26.440
The catering company and the stage crew

13:23.400 --> 13:26.440
did it all last night.

13:26.480 --> 13:28.800
Everyone was signed in, then signed out,

13:28.840 --> 13:30.640
and no-one's visited since.

13:30.680 --> 13:33.440
Yes, well, best to check, anyway, just to be

13:30.680 --> 13:33.440
on the safe side.

13:33.480 --> 13:35.080
So, the killer's intention

13:35.120 --> 13:38.360
was for us to believe that a worn pin and

13:35.120 --> 13:38.360
a badly timed swim

13:38.400 --> 13:40.680
led to the unfortunate death of Stevie Smith.

13:42.200 --> 13:44.520
JP: And you don't believe it, Chief?

13:46.600 --> 13:48.320
No.

13:48.360 --> 13:51.520
